Complicating matters,‭ ‬most if not all genres—rap,‭ ‬rock,‭ ‬country,‭ ‬jazz,‭ ‬folk,‭ ‬just to name a few—have spawned multiple sub and sub-sub genres within their domain.  Arguably the sub-genre of Heavy Metal rock has become one of the most diverse and expressive genres of all popular music in the past‭ ‬40‭ ‬years. It is expressive because it displays a wide range of emotions,‭ ‬although they tend to lean toward the darker side of the spectrum. It is diverse in that quite soon after the beginnings of the genre,‭ ‬people started to realize that it had real flexibility and started to take advantage of it to create their own sub-genre,‭ ‬which then was followed by sub-sub-genres,‭ ‬and the chain continues until today. 

Today we have reached a point in the heavy metal movement where there are so many niches of groups that it is hard to determine what exactly heavy metal is. It has grown to incorporate so many themes from other genres,‭ ‬but like everything else,‭ ‬it spawned from somewhere. In order to properly understand the metal music that exists everywhere today,‭ ‬one must first understand what the metal movement is,‭ ‬and why it’s a movement rather than just a genre.

‎	‏Metal is,‭ ‬in many ways,‭ ‬a movement defined by darkness. Metal can be considered a‭ “‬music of more‭”—‬more bass,‭ ‬more volume,‭ ‬more violence,‭ ‬more theatricality. Less primitivism,‭ ‬more chops‭; ‬people in metal bands really know how to play their instrument,‭ ‬and it comes through in the music. Metal is also—although it may not come as a surprise—a movement that is heavily drug induced. There was a psychedelic drug boom in the mid-70‭’‬s that led to people getting crazier,‭ ‬leading to them to make crazy,‭ ‬other-worldly records,‭ ‬using the drugs as a scapegoat for their creation. It possesses many dark,‭ ‬visceral qualities,‭ ‬which was very new to the music scene because a large amount of popular music had qualities that weren’t true to the darker side of the emotional spectrum. Also,‭ ‬later generations of metal have taken some of their influence from the dark,‭ ‬visceral qualities that were so present in the Romantic Era. Lyrics such as the following express the darkness that is such a staple of the movement:‭ (‬Byrne‭)‬


	
These lyrics from Helter Skelter display the darker side of the Beatles. It exhibits an up and down,‭ ‬supposedly that of drugs. This song is considered by some to be one of the first Heavy Metal songs. It was a response to a Rolling Stones song that was also on the heavier,‭ ‬darker side. The Beatles wanted to prove that they could be just as heavy as the Stones,‭ ‬so they put that song on‭ ‬The White Album.

A few decades before the Surrealist artists began painting their dreamlike works, the artist Henri Rousseau was carefully crafting his own dreams, literally and figuratively. The Dream, a 1910 painting by the famous Post-Impressionist artist, represents not only a woman in awe at the wonders of the land she visits within a dream, but also Rousseau’s own personal dreams and goals as a painter. Since beginning his work, he dreamed of recognition, acceptance, and praise by other artists and art lovers, and found that he was faced with a difficult internal dilemma to achieve this aspiration. The Dream is Henri Rousseau’s work that best reflects his career-long internal struggle: to either conform to or mimic certain styles of painting in order to be accepted by the critical art world he so adored, or to allow himself to be creatively independent and unique, leaving his own path as he went.
Before one can analyze The Dream through this perspective, one must first be somewhat familiar with Rousseau’s biographical story. Henri Rousseau was born on May 21, 1844, in the town of Laval in northwest France. His father was a tinsmith and hardware dealer who “enjoyed bourgeois prosperity” (Shattuck 47). Growing up, he received no formal training in the arts; instead, he was employed until the age of forty working for France as a gabelou, or employee of the municipal toll service, although he received the misnomer sobriquet of douanier, a customs inspector (Shattuck 46). The death of his first wife, Clémence, which followed the deaths of eight infant children, left Rousseau with only one child, a daughter named Julia, and immense grief (Shattuck 49). He therefore hoped to take refuge in a new life and pursued painting to offer him comfort and fresh beginnings. Unlike contemporary colleagues of Rousseau who sentimentalize and romanticize the peasant in painting, he is essentially a folk painter and has the hopes and dreams of the average member of his class.
Rousseau’s obsession with being accepted by the art world is somewhat understandable when evaluated in context: as discussed, he was not only uneducated in the ways of formal painting and began his career at a much older age, but he was producing works at the same time as many other talented and better-known modern artists. Though working for many years already, Rousseau did not begin to receive proper recognition for his art until around the same time that Matisse had begun crafting a reputation as an artist. In the book Modern French Painters, author Jan Gordon asserts that the two, while technically competitors in the art arena, were different not only in style and subject matter but also their reasons for painting in the first place: “Matisse was a painter who conceived a terror of painting in a trite way, while Rousseau’s desire was to paint a picture so conventional that he would be admitted to the Artiste Français” (92).

Many a great thinker has postulated an intimate connection between ethics and aesthetics, between truth and beauty. I believe that at a fundamental level there is a reason for this. As John Keats says in “Ode on a Grecian Urn”, “Beauty is truth, truth beauty- That is all / Ye know on earth, and all ye need to know.” Much of what we know in life is learned via education or experience. However, we seem to appreciate ethics and aesthetics, as Keats implies, without being taught in these expected ways. Both ethics and aesthetics are an attempt to describe rather then prescribe. Our studies of morality and beauty are, for the most part, attempts to explain why a piece of art or literature is beautiful, or why an action is moral, rather than a set of rules for judging, or creating, good art or moral behavior. 
	More to the point, criticism of art or morals is never able to fully capture the essence of what is good or what is beautiful. A conversation about the worth of da Vinci's Mona Lisa, for example, may center around concepts like foreground, background, contrast, or cultural context, but in the end, these do not describe why it is good art. Rather, when one is asked about a favorite work of art or literature it is common to hear a phrase similar to, “There's just something about it” preceding a more complex or critical explanation. I believe that both art and morals can never be completely reduced to a description of their qualities. As Flannery O'Connor says, “A story is a way to say something that can't be said any other way . . . you tell a story because a statement would be inadequate.” No matter how completely we describe the properties of a work of literature, there is something transcendent which is still left. I believe that ethics has this same property. As Wittgenstein says, “It is clear that ethics cannot be expressed. / Ethics is transcendental. / . I suggest that it is this “something”, this je ne sais quoi, which is art and morality's most powerful attribute, and that this transcendental nature of both ethics and aesthetics provides a connection point between them.
	I believe that morality and art are so closely related because we experience both of them most powerfully at a noumenally, to use a Kantian term. They impact us at a level that can be experienced, but not fully explained. This link is even stronger when it comes to the art of literature. As McKean says, “What most distinguishes literature from the other arts, what is, in truth, unique about the art, is its moral quality. It may be that moral standards are inappropriate to other arts, music, for instance, but they seem to be as relevant to literature as they are to life itself. Living necessarily involves values. . . . Literature is important to us precisely because of the values we find there” .

The Germany of today is considered a strong force, a united country with its own blend of culture from within the shadows of the alps in München, all the way to Baltic sea city of Kiel.  The same culture can be felt from Köln on the river Rhine, through the centre of Germany to the Saxon city of Dresden located on the Elbe. With such a unique culture, it shouldn't be surprising that Germany as we now know it comes from several different sources, and tribes. 

Germania is the ancestral land of the Germans. The origins of the name are highly disputed among scholars and historians. Tacitus claimed that the name came from a Germanic Tribe known then as Tungrians, and that they had previously been known as Germans before they crossed the Rhine and battled the Gaulish forces (Tacitus, 98.) Julius Caesar first used the word “Germanus” in his commentary on the Gallic Wars where he put down the Gauls and battled with Germanic tribes which crossed the Rhine often under mischievous premisses. He took this word from The Gauls themselves, and used it to distinguish between those which he had conquered (The Gauls) and those which he had not. While the origin is uncertain, some believe it referred to a neighbor in the Gaulish language. In the first chapter, of his first book on these wars, Julius Caesar notes: “Germans, who dwell beyond the Rhine, with whom they (The Gauls) are continually waging war.....They contend with the Germans in almost daily battles.” (Julius Caesar, 50-40 BC) Others claim the meaning comes from the spear that they used in warfare, known as a ger (O.E.D, 2010), or perhaps from the Old Irish word garim meaning “to shout”, which indicated the Germans were loud, or noisy. (Names of Germany) 

 The early Roman historian Tacitus recorded in his AD 98 writing “De Origine et situ Germanorum”, which told of the origins of the Germans, that “I should regard (The Germans) as aboriginal, and not mixed at all with other races through immigration or intercourse. For, in former times it was not by land but on shipboard that those who sought to emigrate would arrive.......Who would leave Asia, or Africa, for Italy for Germany, with its wild country, its inclement skies, its sullen manners and aspect, unless indeed it were his home?(SIC)” (Tacitus, 98) 

And who would leave Rome for Germania? Certainly not the Romans, not yet at least. They would send out their conquests into the lands of Germania for goods, and lead the occasional land campaign but in the end they mostly returned back home to their sprawling empire. So as the Germanic tribes began appearing in the middle of the first century, they lived on the borders of the Roman Empire and traded their goods taken from the land, and their skills by serving within the ranks of the Roman army, (Ozment, 2005 pg. 17.)

The play Twelfth Night seems to say that although disguise is in fact useful in perpetrating long bouts of deception, in the end a person must reject that newly formed guise, or else risk losing themselves forever in the process. A big problem with ending a deception, however, is that one may find themselves alienated in the process. Therefore, in the end, one must decide between one’s own self preservation, or the preservation of relationships with those around them. For although some will respond neutrally to discovering that they’ve been tricked, still others will not take the deception so lightly, and will be likely be offended by the whole charade.
The topic of deception in gender role reversal is especially problematic, because it brings up many side issues, perhaps the most important one being, why? Why does the subject feel the need to shirk their own identity and take up a disguise in the form of the opposite gender? In Viola’s case, it is obviously a form of self protection.: “I’ll bring you to a captain in this town/ Where lie my maiden weeds, by whose gentle help/ I was preserved to serve this noble count…” (5.1.247-249)
Having newly arrived in a foreign land, Viola feels it necessary to pretend to be a man to protect herself from would be attackers. Viola’s plan works, but it also alienates her from the women around her, cutting her off from an important support system. To make matters worse, she is apparently so convincing at appearing to be a man that Olivia confuses her with Sebastian, and in effect falls in love with her. “Whither, my lord? Cesario, husband, stay.” (5.1.138) On top of that, she also has to deal with suppressed romantic desires between her and Orsino: “Boy, thou hast said to me a thousand times/ Thou never shouldst love woman like to me.” (5.1. 260-261)
Although this may be a somewhat progressive attitude, to the modern reader, Twelfth Night may be seen as an illustration of how deception may help facilitate the unveiling of suppressed emotions, especially in the cases of Olivia and Orsino. Certain passages seem to hint that the aforesaid characters may have unexpressed subconscious desires that the appearance of Viola/Cesario forces them to deal with. For instance, is Olivia attracted to Cesario because Cesario appears to be a man, or does Olivia really secretly harbor feelings for women? One would argue that this is probably not the case, because Shakespeare’s character Olivia seems more likely to be parodying those people of his time period who judge others only upon their looks. 
This is evidenced by the ease with which Olivia switches her romantic ardors from Cesario to Sebastian, and begins to regard Cesario/Viola as family rather than a love interest: “A sister, you are she.” (5.1.315)

German colonial rule has been noted by various observers for its brutality, notably with respect to the genocide of the Ovaherero and Nama in German South West Africa. Of course nothing so broad as an entire colonial empire can be accounted for by such a simple description. The German colonial empire was as varied in policies and ruling style as it was in geography. Educational provision across the colonies was similarly diverse. When the British took over German East Africa (Tanganyika) in 1919, they found a large population of educated and literate Africans. German educational efforts in Kamerun and other colonies were also praised by contemporary authors. 
The situation in South West Africa (present-day Namibia) presented a stark contrast.  Unlike in East Africa, where the government established state schools and played a prominent role in the education of the natives, in South West Africa the task of native education was left almost entirely to missionary societies that received limited government support. The government did however invest significant resources towards the education of Europeans in the colony, establishing s system of state schools as well as more heavily supporting and regulating missionary schools. These educational policies had longstanding effects on South West Africa, even after German rule. While other German colonies boasted significant numbers of literate and educated Africans, in South West Africa “the overwhelming majority of the population remained untouched, uneducated, and illiterate.” Various social, political, and economic factors led to the divergent experience of South West Africa. This paper seeks to expand the discussion by identifying these factors and paying particular attention to new research on the attitudes of settlers and colonial authorities to native Africans.
There is a wealth of literature dealing with education in the German colonial empire specifically. Most of these sources are in German and were written in the early twentieth century, during or shortly after the period of German colonial rule. The aim of early works was primarily to describe the features of educational systems in these colonies. Later writings in English expanded the discourse through comparative studies of education in the various German colonies and more detailed analyses of specific aspects of education. These studies illustrated significant differences in the educational systems of different colonies. The most prominent work to explicitly address the topic of this paper is Cohen’s study of education in South West Africa and East Africa. Cohen compares the educational systems of the two colonies and discusses the factors that account for the differences between them. According to Cohen, the large settler population of South West Africa explains many of the distinguishing aspects of the colony’s educational system.
Compared to Germany’s other colonial possessions, South West Africa had a moderately temperate climate, although much of the territory is covered by arid desert. The European population of South West Africa reflected the relatively hospitable conditions. By 1913 nearly 15,000 whites lived in South West Africa, while only 5,336 lived in the colony with the next largest settler population, East Africa.

The United States of America and Mexico are an example of two nations which at one time were beset by an enduring rivalry which spanned 57 years, from 1836 to 1893. (Diehl and Goerts 2000 p. 145).  The high-water mark of this rivalry was the Mexican-American War of 1846-1848, where the United States attacked and defeated Mexico and secured for itself Texas and the American Southwest as new territory.  Many other clashes happened between the two nations, finally abating just before the First World War.   The rivalry began as Americans and Mexicans clashed on key issues such as religion, culture and tradition and had a major clash of material interests (Schmitt 1974 p. 30-31).   
	This is not unlike many other nations who have an enduring rivalry with a neighbor.  Nations which share a border tend to have clashes of interests which lend to the creation of rival positions between the nations.  The United States and Mexico are not unlike many other enduring rivalries between nations which share a common border.  David M. Pletcher (1977) states that “Only in Mexico and Cuba can one find long-lasting overarching American diplomatic problems” (p. 41).  Indeed, both of these nations are geographically close to the United States and have been rivals to the United States, while other nations in Latin America enjoy and have enjoyed good relations with the United States.   
	Religious issues created a rift between the two nations, a problem which has beset many nations through history.  Sally Frahm (2001) states that ”if in the twentieth century Americans were opposed to fascism and communism, in the eighteenth and nineteenth they were opposed to Catholicism and monarchy”  (p.86).  Not unlike the Cold War’s rivalry between the United States and the Soviet Union was part ideological struggle and part a competition over interests each nation deemed vital. In this case, however, the ideological struggles weren’t based on the political structure but on instead the religious preferences of the United States and Mexico.  This distrust grew from the distrust between the English and Spanish.  Inheriting these feelings of distrust from their former colonial rulers was a major obstacle in the establishment of amiable foreign relations between the United States and Mexico.
	Diehl and Goerts (2000) list 17 disputes between Mexico and the United States in the 57-year rivalry period.   The majority of disputes between the rivalry period described by Diehl and Goerts are territorial issues relating to border raids from Mexican territory into Mexico and other frontier problems.  Border raids by bandits and outlaws from on American border towns were a major problem which remained until both the United States and Mexico exerted military force on their borders (Schmitt 1974 p. 97).  
Schmitt (1974) explains the rivalry between the two nation began to abate as “Mexico became clearly dependent on the United States in a substantial way” (p. 109) and finally ended as American ambitions “changed from territorial expansion to economic intervention into Mexico” (p.110) in the later part of the 19th Century.

Fifteen‭ ‬years ago I became suddenly and unexpectedly disabled by an illness I never knew existed. 

 I was a nurse at the time. I had chosen my profession out of a deeply entrenched need for the safety and security I didn't have as a child. ‭"‬You'll always be able to find work‭; ‬people will always get sick.‭" ‬was the mantra I heard over and over as I reached adolescence and beyond. So--‭ ‬even though my dream was to be a scientist or a journalist-preferably a little of both,‭ ‬I chose nursing. 

Nevertheless,‭ ‬there I was:‭ ‬46‭ ‬years old and single,‭ ‬no money in the bank to speak of and unable to work. To this day I am disabled,‭ ‬and after‭ ‬15‭ ‬years of living on Social Security Disability,‭ ‬I have literally nothing left that I can call‭ "‬mine.‭" ‬I get by,‭ ‬but every day is a struggle and an assault on my security,‭ ‬safety and self-esteem. Nothing in my life is certain anymore,‭ ‬yet,‭ ‬there is one thing that I know to be true. I could not have gotten by for all these years were it not for the help of my family and a few good friends,‭ ‬no matter how strong I was. And believe me,‭ ‬when real disaster strikes,‭ ‬you do not feel very strong at all. 

My point is that there will always be emergencies in life-big and small.  There are no guarantees and no matter how well one prepares,‭ ‬some things are just too big to overcome on your own. 

I agree wholeheartedly that we in the U.S. need to stop putting all of our eggs in big government's‭ "‬basket‭"; ‬Lord knows it is moldy‭ ‬and falling apart,‭ ‬anyway. Yet I would much rather see Americans learning to trust one another again‭–‬learning to help each other and to ask for help,‭ ‬rather‭ ‬than have each of us individually clambering out to the backyard to build fallout shelters. 

The Conservatives in the US talk about the‭ "‬rugged individualism‭" ‬that built this country‭; ‬but in truth,‭ ‬what kept our forefathers going in hard times wasn't rugged individualism,‭ ‬it was compassion,‭ ‬mutual respect and the sharing of resources. The pioneers who crossed the Rockies in wagon trains didn't make it to the coast by going it alone. 


So,‭ ‬by all means,‭ ‬be prepared. I am. I have a disaster kit‭; ‬first‭ ‬aid supplies,‭ ‬water purifying tablets and plastic sheeting and duct tape for the windows in the event of a biological attack. I have several flashlights and all sorts of batteries,‭ ‬lots and lots of candles and waterproof matches and canned goods,‭ ‬too. If‭ ‬you have the land and the resources for a small farm and the ability to can or preserve your own food-do it. It's a great idea,‭ ‬as is a wood stove,‭ ‬as long as you do not live in an apartment. 

But while you are at it,‭ ‬get to know your neighbors.

Sometime in the fifth or sixth century BCE, a prince who would one day be called Buddha was born. Over the course of his life, he renounced the world and became enlightened, and his teachings led to the formation of Buddhism—the most orthodox sect of which is known as Theravada Buddhism. The religion is around twenty five hundred years old; it looks different today than it did when Buddha was alive. This can be seen all over, for instance in the Theravada nation of Sri Lanka, where the annual water-cutting ceremony is observed. Monks and laymen alike participate in this ceremony, and it holds some religious significance, despite Buddha never teaching about any festivity of the sort. These differences run all the way from the superficial traditions to the soteriological core of the religion. The Theravada Buddhist community, both from the monastic perspective and from the lay perspective, has had to change its doctrinal principles over time. This can be attributed to forces both external and internal, both hostile and benign.
	There are a number of qualifying terms this discussion will make frequent use of. There is the concept of internal versus external. Here, an internal force is defined as a force borne of members of the Buddhasasana, regardless of monastic status. An external force is any force from non-Buddhists. A hostile force is any force that damages or intends to damage the Buddhist community—a force borne of a negative perception of Buddhism. A benign force is a force that does not wish to harm or help the Buddhist community—though it may end up doing one or the other as a byproduct. These terms will come up repeatedly throughout this discussion.
	First, it is important to investigate the basics of the religion—the doctrines that lie at the core of Theravada Buddhism. Buddhists seek refuge in the triple gem of the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma is essentially comprised of the Tripitaka—the three baskets—of Buddhist text. The Sutta Pitaka contains all the Suttas, the Vinaya Pitaka contains the disciplinary rules, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka contains the metaphysical components of Buddhism. The metaphysical notions consist of things like Anatta—no soul, Dukkha—inherent suffering in life, and Anicca—impermanence of everything. Only by recognizing these concepts can one end Sansara, the cycle of death and rebirth, which happens continuously. Along with Sansara will end lobha—desire, dosa—hatred, and moha—delusion, when one becomes enlightened. In the Vinaya Pitaka, rules for life are set forth. For laymen, there are five precepts (I shall not kill, I shall not lie, I shall not steal, I shall not misbehave sexually, and I shall not take intoxicating substances). For monks, there are many more disciplinary rules to be followed. The most fundamental doctrinal notion in Buddhism is the notion of the four noble truths. First, Dukkha; the truth that life is suffering. Second, that attachment causes suffering. Third, that suffering can be overcome.

So, I'm thinkin' about becoming a social worker, ya know? Figured I'd go with the Division of Family and Children Services and help out those kids who've had a rough go of it, the ones who've been abused or forgotten.  I wanna lend a hand to families too, 'cause sometimes they just need a little extra support.  

See, for me, social work ain't just a job, it's a way of life. I've always wanted to help people, but I didn't know how 'til I figured out what I was good at.  I went to college and got my degree in Psychology, but I still felt like something was missing.

Then one summer, I met this kid, just sixteen, sitting on my friend's couch lookin' like he'd seen a ghost. Turns out, he was runnin' from his parents, who weren't exactly the nicest folks. I didn't know what to do, but I knew I had to help. I talked to the cops, told 'em I was a psychology grad.  They asked me to talk to the parents 'cause they couldn't do much for the kid.  Man, those parents were somethin' else! They were all nervous and makin' excuses about their son bein' a manipulator. It was a wake-up call for me. That's when I knew I wanted to be a social worker, someone who could actually make a difference for kids like him.

And let's talk about social justice, somethin' that's super important in this field.  Society always talks about how much it cares about individuals, but then it tries to cram everyone into the same mold.  Why can't we celebrate our differences instead of tryin' to be just like everyone else?  I've always been my own person, standin' up for what I believe in.  I protested against injustice whenever I could, dyed my hair crazy colors, wore clothes that showed who I was, even joined the GSBA.  I'm all about fightin' for what's right, and social work is the perfect way to do that.

This piece is gonna break down the sleep-trouble thingy called insomnia, lookin' at why it happens. We'll check out two main ideas: what's going on inside ya (the biological stuff) and what's happening around ya (the sociocultural stuff).

First off, let's talk about sleep problems in general. You got your main sleep trouble types: the ones that stand alone (like insomnia), the ones that come with other mental stuff (like anxiety or depression), and the ones caused by stuff like medical stuff or drugs.

Now, insomnia is a real pain. It's when you can't fall asleep or stay asleep, and it's been bugging ya for at least a month. Then there are other sleep issues like oversleeping (hypersomnia) or narcolepsy, which is when ya suddenly fall asleep, even when you don't want to.

So, the "what's inside ya" idea says that genes and your body's insides play a big role. There's this part of your brain called the hypothalamus, which has special cells called orexins that tell you when to sleep and when to wake.

One study found that these orexin cells have something called GABAB receptors, which are like tiny switches that control sleep. When these switches are turned on, it makes you sleepy. But if they're messed up, well, that could be why you can't sleep!

Now, the "what's around ya" idea says that your life stuff matters too. Your job, your family, your money – all that stuff can affect your sleep. Imagine if you're stressed out because you're worried about money or work – it's gonna be hard to sleep!

Alright, listen up! Let's talk about this thing called Central Auditory Processing Disorder, or CAPD for short. It's basically when your brain has trouble makin' sense of sounds, even if your ears are workin' just fine. Think of it like this: your ears are like a radio receiver, pickin' up all the signals, but the brain is the speaker, and sometimes the speaker is messed up. 

So, how do you know if someone's got CAPD? Well, there are some red flags, like havin' trouble followin' conversations in a noisy place, mixin' up words, or missin' things when someone's talkin'. It's not that they're not listenin', it's just their brain's havin' a hard time sortin' out all the noise.

Now, imagine you're a teacher in a regular classroom. What can ya do to help a kid with CAPD? Well, ya gotta be patient and creative.  Maybe try lettin' them sit closer to the front,  use visual aids, and break down instructions into smaller steps.  Remember, everyone learns differently, and with a little extra help, kids with CAPD can still succeed!

Listen up, folks!  This play, Twelfth Night, it's like, totally saying that while disguises are great for pulling off con games for a long time, eventually, you gotta ditch the fake persona or you're gonna lose yourself completely.  The thing is, stopping the charade can be a real pain in the neck 'cause you might end up alienating all your friends. So, it's a tough call:  stay true to yourself or keep the peace? Some people are cool with being tricked, but others? Not so much. They'll be totally offended. 

Now, pretending to be the opposite gender is a whole other can of worms. Why do people even bother with that?  Why ditch your real identity and pretend to be someone you're not?  Well, in Viola's case, it's all about survival. She's in a strange land, and she needs to protect herself from creepy dudes.  So, she becomes Cesario, a dude. It works, but it also cuts her off from other women, which is kinda a bummer.  

Get this – she's so good at playing a guy that Olivia, this rich lady, totally falls for her!   "Whither, my lord? Cesario, husband, stay." She's even got Orsino, who's like, totally into her, but she's pretending to be a dude! It's a mess! "Boy, thou hast said to me a thousand times/ Thou never shouldst love woman like to me."  

So, maybe this play is saying that pretending can help people figure out their true feelings? Or maybe not.  Olivia's all over Cesario, but is that because he's a guy or is she secretly into women?  Who knows?  

Shakespeare's got a way of making you think, you know? He's like, "What's real anyway?"

Alright, so listen up!  This whole German colonial thing, yeah?  It wasn't all sunshine and rainbows, especially for the Ovaherero and Nama people in South West Africa.  Talk about a massacre!  But hey, you can't just paint a whole empire with one brush, right?  Germany had a bunch of different colonies, each with its own style. 

Same goes for schools.  When the Brits took over German East Africa (Tanganyika) in 1919, they were surprised to find a bunch of educated folks already there.  Seems those Germans did a decent job in some places.  But then you got South West Africa, which was a whole different story.  

Unlike East Africa where the government built schools and stuff, in South West Africa, they left it all to the missionaries.  Those missionaries got some government support, but not much.  Meanwhile, the Germans were all about educating their own people, building fancy schools and supporting those missionary ones too.  This messed things up big time for South West Africa. While other colonies had tons of educated Africans, South West Africa was like, "Nah, we good." Most folks there were still stuck in the dark ages, can't read, can't write, you know the drill.

Why the big difference?  Well, that's what this paper's all about.  We gotta dig into the whole settler scene and figure out what the bigwigs were thinking.  There's a ton of books about German schools, mostly written back in the day, but we need to take a closer look at what went on in South West Africa.  Some smart folks like Cohen have already compared South West Africa to East Africa and found some clues.  They think the big white population in South West Africa had a lot to do with it.

South West Africa wasn't as hot and sweaty as some other colonies, but they still had a ton of desert.  And guess what?  More white folks wanted to live there! By 1913, almost 15,000 whites were calling South West Africa home, way more than any other colony.

Man, music these days is wild! Like, there's so many different kinds of music now, it's crazy. Rock, pop, rap, country, jazz, folk—you name it, there's a genre for it. And get this, each of those genres has like, a million sub-genres and sub-sub-genres. It's like a never-ending musical family tree!

But let's talk about heavy metal, because that's where things get really interesting. That stuff's been around for ages, but it's exploded in the last 40 years. Heavy metal is all about feeling things, you know? And not the happy-go-lucky kind of feelings either. We're talking dark, intense emotions, the kind that make you wanna headbang until your head falls off. 

It's also super diverse. People realized early on that heavy metal wasn't just one thing, it was a whole playground for creativity. So they started making their own sub-genres, then sub-sub-genres, and so on. 

Now it's like, what even IS heavy metal anymore? It's borrowed stuff from every other genre, but it still has that core, that dark, powerful energy.  

To understand heavy metal today, you gotta understand where it came from. It's more than just music, it's a movement. A movement fueled by darkness, loudness, and a whole lotta attitude.

Think about it: more bass, more volume, more guitars screaming, more theatricality. It's like the music scene said "screw subtlety" and cranked everything up to 11.

And yeah, let's not forget the drugs. The 70s were wild, man. All those psychedelics made people think differently, do different things, make different music. And heavy metal was born from that chaos.

They weren't afraid to explore the dark side of life, something that was kinda taboo in mainstream music back then. They drew inspiration from the Romantics, those poets who were all about intense feelings and dark themes.  

Even the Beatles got in on the action. Their song "Helter Skelter" is a prime example. It's raw, it's chaotic, it's a glimpse into the darkness that was brewing.

Alright, so picture this: before all those fancy Surrealist dudes were painting their crazy dreams, there was this guy, Henri Rousseau. He was like, way ahead of his time. This dude wasn't just painting dreams, he was *living* them, ya know? His famous painting, "The Dream," from 1910, shows this lady totally blown away by the cool stuff she sees in her dream. But here's the kicker - it's also about Rousseau's own dreams, like, what he wanted out of life as an artist.  

See, he always wanted people to get his art, to be all "WOW, this guy's amazing!" But there was this big problem: he had this crazy fight going on inside his head. Should he paint like everyone else to get famous, or should he just do his own thing and be different? "The Dream" is like his big, messy answer to that question.

Now, to understand what's going on, you gotta know a little about this guy. He was born way back in 1844 in a dusty French town. His dad was some kind of rich merchant, but Rousseau didn't get any fancy art training. He spent years working for the government, collecting taxes and stuff, until he was like, forty! Then, tragedy struck - his wife and almost all his kids died.  He decided to paint to escape his sadness and start fresh. Unlike those other artists who painted fancy pictures of peasants, Rousseau was a regular guy with regular dreams.

Rousseau really, really wanted to be a big deal in the art world.  He was starting late, and all these other artists were already famous. He was like, "Hey, I'm good too!" but nobody was listening.  This other artist, Matisse, was getting all the attention, and Rousseau was stuck in the shadows. This guy Gordon wrote a book about French art, and he said that Matisse was all about being different and unique, while Rousseau just wanted to paint something so normal that people would finally accept him.

So, lotsa brainy folks, like, way smarter than me, think there's a super close link between being good and lookin' good, you know, like truth and beauty.  I kinda get it. Like, that poet Keats, he said somethin' like, "Beauty is truth, truth beauty - that's all you need to know." 

We learn stuff, right? Like, history, math, all that, but stuff like right and wrong, and what's pretty... that just feels different.  It's not like someone taught us to like a sunset or feel bad when someone's mean. It's just... there.

Think about it. We can try to explain what makes art great or what makes somethin' right, but it's kinda hard to put it into words. You ever try to tell someone why you love a certain song? You might say somethin' about the beat, or the lyrics, but it ain't the whole story, ya know? There's just this... *something*

Same with good stuff like kindness or honesty. We can talk about why it's important, but it's more than just words. It's like, deep down, you just *know* it's good.

That's why I think art and good stuff are connected.  They're both kinda magical, ya know? They move us in ways we can't always explain. It's like this feeling you get when you read a super good book, or see a painting that just blows you away. It's more than just pretty colors or a good story. It's somethin' deeper.

So, lemme tell ya about Germany, alright? It's a powerhouse, a real unified crew, with its own crazy cool culture, from the Alps in München all the way to the Baltic Sea in Kiel.  You feel the same vibe from Köln on the Rhine to Dresden in Saxony by the Elbe.  It's a mix of all sorts of stuff, ya know?  

See, Germany's got a wild history, a whole bunch of different tribes and stuff that came together to make it what it is today.  Folks call this ancient land "Germania," but where that name came from, well, that's a mystery even smarter folks than me can't solve. Tacitus, this old dude who wrote about Germans way back when, thought it came from a tribe called the Tungrians. They were called Germans before they crossed the Rhine and went head-to-head with the Gauls, ya see. (Tacitus, 98, get it?  Like, 98 AD!)  Then there's Julius Caesar, who, back in the day, used the word "Germanus" to talk about these pesky tribes he was fighting near the Rhine.  He nicked it from the Gauls, probably, a way to tell who he'd conquered and who he hadn't. Some think it was just a neighborly term in Gaulish, you know, like "Hey, those Germans over there." (Names of Germany) Other folks say it came from the spear they used, called a "ger," or maybe it meant "shouty" in some old language, 'cause Germans were known for being loud. (O.E.D, 2010, whatever that means).

This other Roman dude, Tacitus, wrote a book called "De Origine et situ Germanorum" way back in 98 AD. It's about where Germans came from, and he's like, "These guys?  They're the real deal, no mixing with other folks, they just *were*.  Nobody would leave Asia or Africa for this wild, cold, grumpy place unless it was home, right?" (Tacitus, 98) 

And who'd want to leave Rome for Germania?  Not the Romans, not at first anyway.  But they'd send their guys out to get stuff and fight the occasional battle, but mostly, they went back to their big ol' empire.

So, these Germanic tribes, they were hanging out on the edge of Rome's land, trading their stuff and even fighting for Rome in their army.  (Ozment, 2005 pg. 17)

Man, I was staring at this thing, my brain just kinda... empty. Not thinking, just seeing. Like, super focused but not really 'getting' it, y'know? Thoughts were popping in and out, but nothin' stuck. It was like my mind was just... flowing with what I was looking at.

This artist pal once told me to check out this book, "Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain" or somethin'.  Always wanted to draw, ever since I was a kid, and this book was supposed to teach ya how, like, what a pencil is and how your brain even sees lines. 

One trick in there is to picture a box around whatever ya lookin' at.  Like, say you've got a bowl of fruit on a table in a kitchen that's connected to a dining room, bam! Now it's just the bowl of fruit, simple as that.

But staring at this thing... I couldn't do it. It was just too much, too mind-blowing. Picasso had his blue stuff, Monet went crazy for green, Renaissance dudes loved all the colors.  My art was gonna be different, man, this was gonna be "Work in Brown," the start of my masterpiece.

So I grabbed my tool, muscles gettin' tense and loose as I moved my hand, like, my mind was telling my hand what to do.  Water was swirlin', smooth and clear, and stuff was breakin' off and just... gone.  Muscles gettin' jumpy, I slammed the toilet handle again.  This brown thing wasn't budging, stuck like a bug on the bottom.

Mop in hand, feet apart, tie chokin' me, I frowned at this mess someone left for us bathroom cleaners at Rite Aid.  A few more flushes, a few more moments of peaceful thinkin', then I grabbed the toilet paper, wrapped it around my hand like a giant oven mitt, and dove in. Just like a mom checkin' on the turkey in the oven...

Yo, check this out.  Junior drivers are croakin' behind the wheel, man. It's a real bummer. Why? Well, the brainiacs at the National Institutes of Health say those teen brains ain't quite ready for the insanity of the road yet.  And, let's face it, they're green as grass. Not only do they cause more wrecks, but they're more likely to flip their cars, speed like crazy, and end up in the ditch.  

Talk about a recipe for disaster!

And get this, having your buddies in the car makes it even worse.  Some smarty-pants in California did a study and found that the more passengers a teen has, the more likely they are to crash.  Duh!

So, some states are tryin' to fix this mess by giving teens these temporary licenses that limit their driving time and how many friends can tag along.  But, honestly, that's just a band-aid on a gaping wound. The real problem is that teen drivers, statistically speaking, are just not cut out for the dangers of the road.  This psychologist dude, Marvin Zuckerman, thinks 18 is even too young to get a license.  He says teenagers are wired to take risks just for the rush, which, let's be real, is a bad combo with a steering wheel.  

We gotta delay driving until they're a little older, when they've calmed down and don't feel the need to live life on the edge.  Otherwise, we're gonna have a highway full of carnage.  Just you wait—the Baby Boomers' kids are gonna be hitting the road soon, and that's a whole lot of new drivers with questionable skills.

Here's what we need: a national law that says no one under 18 can drive. Schools can still teach 'em about driving, but no keys until they're older.  We can still have those temporary permits and practice hours, but no exceptions.  That way, we can keep everyone safe.

It ain't rocket science, folks.

So, I was digging through these old Edison movies at the Library of Congress, you know, the ones from way back when. I found fifteen of these "trick films" from between 1895 and 1901. These flicks, they're all about tricking your eyes with clever editing. Basically, I wanted to figure out how they made these tricks work and see if any of them got fancy later on. 

Most of the time, these early trick films were pretty simple. They were like little plays, all set up in front of a camera like a stage. No fancy camera moves, just straight-ahead shots of people doing their thing.  Think of it like a vaudeville show, but on film! You know, the audience always sees the whole picture at once, just like on a stage. 

These tricksters mostly stuck to long shots or medium shots, never getting close-up on anyone's face.  They even kept the action limited to side-to-side movements  - no walking towards or away from the camera. Like in this film "Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel" from 1900, the actors just walk back and forth, never leaving that stage-like area. 

And get this, each trick film was usually just one long shot, like a single scene.  They couldn't really tell a full story because they were so short. They were more like little magic tricks or gags, lasting maybe a minute or less. 

But here's the kicker: what looks like one shot to us might actually be several shots spliced together to make the illusion work. Take "The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots" from 1895, for example.  If you watch closely, you'll see the moment where they switch out the "head" – it's like a hidden camera trick!

Alright, lemme tell ya 'bout this dude John Taylor, real upstanding guy, straight outta Caroline. This fella was all about the Republican thing, ya know?  Didn't matter that he was a farmer, that life and his little stint in politics made him a real firebrand when it came to folks' freedom and how the government should run things. He was all about farms and stuff, thought it was the best job in the world, and that's what shaped his whole take on the government, the Constitution, even the courts.

See, John thought America had a shot at gettin' things right 'cause we didn't have no old traditions messin' things up. We could build somethin' new, somethin' based on people takin' care of themselves. He was a real believer in rights, the kind you're born with, that can't be touched by the government.  He figured if you mess with one right, they all start to crumble.  And he thought the idea of a "state of nature" where the strong just bulldoze the weak was a load of baloney. Civilization should be better than that.

To make this perfect society, John thought we needed a government that knew folks are a mix of good and bad. He was hard-line on that, thought we gotta be honest about it. He said,"Government's run by people, so it's gonna have all the good and bad that comes with 'em."  He thought good government protected your stuff, helped farmers, and kept big businesses in check. He figured even if the people runnin' things were greedy, a good system would still work out fair.

John believed folks are driven by self-interest, but it ain't always bad. It's only bad when it makes folks want to screw over others.  A good government keeps that in check.  He was all about the Constitution, but he didn't think just readin' the words was enough. You gotta understand what the guys who wrote it meant.  He thought the Declaration of Independence was even more important 'cause it made it clear America was a bunch of separate states, not just one big country.

So, check it out. We were tracking how many folks were ditching their cars for bikes or walking or whatever, right? But in month three, bam!  The numbers nosedived like a cheetah on roller skates. Kinda bummer, ya know?

Winter hit New England, so maybe folks just stopped biking and walking as much.  Plus, December is crazy busy with school stuff ending and holidays kicking in.  People are probably too swamped with exams and gift-wrapping to remember to fill out those log sheets. 

Then, December turned into January, and everyone was on break. Like, no one even needs to be on campus! Then classes start up again in January, and, guess what? Still low numbers! 

You know how it is, things get hyped up at first, then people kinda lose steam.  We tried to pump things up with a "Carpool Challenge Week" in March, and it worked! More people started logging their commutes.  

But here's the deal - keeping people interested when there's a natural lull, plus those big school breaks, is tough.  

Another thing? People love their cars. It's like, built into our brains! So, to get them to ditch the wheels, you gotta give 'em good reasons. 

We gave away cool stuff like gift cards to local places – restaurants, coffee shops, even massages!  I wonder if something bigger, like a sweet bicycle or even a hybrid car, would have made a bigger splash.

We kept the prizes the same the whole time. Maybe if we'd upped the ante as things went on – maybe a couple bikes in December, then a hybrid or electric car in January – things might have stayed super pumped.

Hold onto your hats, folks! Today we're diving deep into the wild world of ETFs, those fancy financial instruments that track stuff like stock indexes or even whole baskets of assets. Think of them like index funds, but way more flexible, like a stock you can buy and sell on the open market.  

These bad boys give you the best of both worlds: the spread-out protection of an index fund and the cool perks of owning individual stocks, like short selling, margin trading, and snagging just one share at a time. Oh, and did I mention they're usually cheaper to own than your average mutual fund? Talk about a win-win!

But hold up! There's always a catch, right? Well, with ETFs, you gotta cough up a commission every time you buy or sell, just like with regular stocks.  And while they offer a ton of choices, it's always smart to double-check if those benefits, like diversification, are really delivering the goods.

Today, we're putting a popular ETF called IHF under the microscope. We're gonna compare it to its top ten holdings, which make up a whopping 63.58% of the whole shebang. These top dogs are like the VIPs of the ETF world, so if we understand them, we're halfway to understanding the whole crew.

We're gonna see if owning just these ten stocks would be just as good, or even better, than owning the whole IHF ETF.  Plus, we'll see if we can find a better way to mix and match these ten stocks to get even better returns, like a financial magic trick!  

First, we'll crunch some numbers to figure out how these ten stocks contribute to the overall return and risk (or Beta) of the ETF. Then, we'll see if these two portfolios - the ETF and the top ten - are truly different, or just playing a game of chance. Stay tuned, folks, it's gonna be a wild ride!

Alright, so check it out, this poem "Dream-Land" by Poe, he thinks it's pretty rad. Now, Poe uses this word "Thulé" a couple times, and some dude named Mabbott figured out it comes from this old dude Virgil. Virgil used it for this island way up north, like beyond the edge of the known world, ya know?  Virgil totally used it, but there's this other dude, Goethe, who Poe was digging big time. This Karl J. Arndt guy, he wrote a whole book about Poe and Goethe's poems, and he reckons Poe was basically copying Goethe.

Goethe, man, he was a big deal. Wrote this epic poem called "Faust," two parts, way back in the day.  Part two has this poem called "The King of Thulé." It's about this king whose wife kicks the bucket after giving him this goblet. He starts drowning his sorrows in booze, missing his queen like crazy.  Then he's all, "Screw this," decides to join his wife, gives his stuff to his kids, except for the goblet, walks to a cliff, tosses the goblet in the ocean, closes his eyes, and bam! Dead. Pretty messed up, right?  

So, the King of Thulé and the dude in Poe's poem, they're kinda like mirror images, like Poe's own messed up feelings bottled up in this poem.  There was even this play version of Faust in 1842,  just before Poe used "Thulé" in his other poem, "The Pit and the Pendulum." 

Poe uses "Thulé" twice in his poems, like bookends, but "The King of Thulé" and "Dream-Land," they're like buddies. In "Dream-Land," the speaker talks about how dark and lonely Thulé is, haunted by dead friends, everything's gray and depressing. Sounds a lot like how the King of Thulé feels after his wife dies, right? 

Goethe was a big deal, and Poe would have known him, even if it was just because he liked Tennyson. Plus, Goethe's stuff was everywhere back then.

Okay, lemme tell ya about this crazy case I heard about. So there's this lady, Jennifer, right? She slipped and fell on some spilled applesauce in a grocery store called D&D. Ouch! Turns out, the manager, Paul, knew about the mess 'cause two employees told him about it. But guess what? He was too busy eating dinner!  Thirty minutes passed and BAM! Jennifer goes down!  

Now, Jennifer's lawyer wants to go after Paul big time with "punitive damages". That means like, extra money to punish him 'cause they think he was super reckless. See, in California, you can get those if someone acts really bad on purpose, or just plain stupid and doesn't care if someone gets hurt. And in this case, they think Paul fits the bill.  

They're going to argue that Paul knew this store was a slip-and-slide! Apparently, there'd been five other falls that year already! But nope, he still wouldn't clean it up.  

It's a bit of a stretch to say he was "despicable," but hey, it's California, anything goes!  They're gonna try to convince the judge that Paul was playing with fire and Jennifer got burned. 

Their story goes like this:  It was a Friday afternoon, 5 p.m. sharp.  One of Paul's guys, Rich, tells him about the applesauce. Paul's like, "Dude, I'm on a break, go away!" Then another employee, Mary, tries to warn him again, and guess what? Same response!  

Finally, at 5:30, poor Jennifer slips and falls, and ouch, she really hurt her back. So now she's suing D&D for all the money they can get.  It's gonna be a showdown in court!

Man, lemme tell ya, four years ago I took this Islam class at CBC, and let me tell ya, things got heated! We were debating whether Islam was a bad religion or not, and it feels even more important today than ever. It's crazy how things have changed since 9/11.  I mean, back then the media was all over Islam, sayin' it was bad news, and now it's like everyone loves it!  Heck, we even got a president named Barack Obama, who's got Muslim roots, can you believe it?!

Now, this book about Muhammad's life, it got me thinkin'. See, I thought Muhammad was a tough guy, conquering tribes and forcing them to become Muslims, but this book paints him as this misunderstood martyr, a humble dude who people just naturally flocked to. It's kinda strange, like they're trying to make him look like some kinda Jesus figure.

And get this, there are some crazy similarities between Jesus and Muhammad. Like, there's this story where Muhammad turns some mutton and milk into enough food for forty guys!  It's like they're tryin' to make Muhammad look like some kinda miracle worker, which, you know, kinda steals thunder from Jesus, if you ask me.

The book's full of stories about people converting to Islam, but a lot of them come from, like, second or third hand accounts. It's all "so-and-so told me, who heard it from so-and-so." It makes you wonder how true it all really is.

The thing that bugs me the most is how they try to make Muhammad out to be this perfect, gentle guy. But history tells a different story, man! He wasn't exactly Mr. Nice Guy. I gotta wonder if Muslims today even know the real story about how Muhammad got his power.

Whoa, man, listen up!  So, you know how Jesus taught his stuff, right?  Well, after he, like, disappeared, Christianity went totally off the rails!  It's like, they added all this extra junk over time, making it way different from the original deal.  

These days, everyone's all about change and progress, ya know?  The old-school folks, they cling to what they know, but they're not gonna be able to stop the tide.  People are gonna start figuring out what was really important to Jesus, and ditch all the extra stuff.

It might take a while, maybe decades, maybe centuries, but it's gonna happen. Christianity's gonna go back to its roots, stripping away all the layers, like turning back time!  Eventually, we'll be worshipping just like they did back in Jesus' day, following only his teachings.

The churches will still be there, but everything will be way more unified.  No more different groups, no more arguments, just everyone on the same page.  Think of it like history reversing itself.  Remember how Christians used to get persecuted?  Then the Romans became Christian themselves!  Or how slavery ended and African-Americans rose to power?  

This big shift in Christianity is gonna be just like that.  It'll go back to the source, back to what Jesus really taught, and it'll bring everyone together.  The key is understanding that Jesus' words were meant metaphorically, not literally.  

So, what happened after Jesus?  Well, before Jesus, there was Judaism, the starting point for it all.  The Jews believed in one God, had scriptures they considered divinely inspired, and they were all about that religious authority.

Man, lemme tell ya about this book, "The Jungle." It's like, a real eye-opener about how messed up people can get when they're all about money and power. I mean, these factory owners, they're like, obsessed with makin' their businesses bigger and richer, no matter who they step on along the way. They're practically demons, those guys.

Take a look at this line from the book: "The line of the buildings stood clear-cut and black against the sky; here and there out of the mass rose the great chimneys, with the river of smoke streaming away to the end of the world".  It's like Upton Sinclair is sayin', "Yo, look at this pollution! It's outta control!"  These owners, they don't even care about the air we breathe or the animals gettin' hurt. They're like, "more profit, more profit!"  

And forget about the workers, man. They're just pawns in this whole game. The owners squeeze 'em dry, makin' 'em work crazy hours, and then BAM! They're out on the street with nothin'. No warning, no nothin'. They don't even get a "thank you" for all their hard work.  Back then, there were no rules or nothin' to protect these poor dudes. They were stuck in a system that was rigged against 'em.

It's like they're slaves, man.  Sinclair even says, "Here is a population, low-class and mostly foreign, hanging always on the verge of starvation and dependent for its opportunities of life upon the whim of men every bit as brutal and unscrupulous as the old-time slave drivers; under such circumstances, immorality is exactly as inevitable, and as prevalent, as it is under the system of chattel slavery."  Harsh, right?

So yeah, "The Jungle" shows how greedy and selfish humans can be when they're chasin' after money. It's a real wake-up call.

So, you see, some writers are real slick, they use tricks to make you *feel* somethin' about stuff, ya know? Like, they pair words together that wouldn't normally hang out, just to make ya think a certain way. Or they pick symbols, like colors, and give 'em a secret meaning, then use 'em to make ya remember that feeling every time you see 'em. F. Scott Fitzgerald, the guy who wrote *The Great Gatsby*, he's a master of this stuff.

He does this whole thing with colors, like gold, green, white, gray, and even red and pink. He builds up this meaning, like a secret code, and then uses those colors to remind ya of that feeling later on.

Take white and gray, for example. Fitzgerald uses these colors a lot, and he makes them mean somethin' special. White, it's like, fancy and all that, while gray is kinda old and faded. He throws these colors around everywhere at the start of the story. Daisy and Jordan, they're always dressed in white, like it's the only color they know. Even Nick, he's wearing white flannels at Gatsby's party, and Tom's got a white shirt on when he meets Myrtle. It's like everyone's wearin' white, and the only time they're not is when Nick's getting a vibe from Gatsby's party, and then it's all these crazy colors, like red and blue, nothin' fancy.

Then Fitzgerald keeps throwin' white and gray at ya, like when Nick goes to work, he goes down "white chasms," or when Gatsby's party guests are just "gray names" to Nick. Even places are white or gray, like the apartment buildings, the cars, the land, even people like that gray old dog-seller.

So, after you've seen white and gray everywhere, Fitzgerald uses 'em to show ya somethin' ain't important, or kinda boring. He uses this with Daisy, too. After a while, he describes her in all white, and suddenly, she doesn't seem so special anymore. She's just another white thing, somethin' Gatsby wants but ain't really real. He keeps doin' this with Daisy, makin' her seem like she's just a part of the pattern, not a real person.

So, check this out. San Diego's a real hot spot for growing stuff, thanks to the killer weather. Tomatoes, citrus, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, peaches, lemons, berries, honey, and peppers - they grow it all! And get this, people are going crazy for organic food here. Like, seriously, there are tons of farms selling it straight to folks, and they have waiting lists longer than my arm!  Organic eggs and milk are the faves, too.  

These organic farms are pretty cool. They give tours, let you hike around, birdwatch, the whole shebang. It's like a win-win: farmers get to be all green and stuff, and people get to learn about where their food comes from. Plus, they get government help for doing it, which is pretty sweet.

Now, here's the thing about organic farming. It's awesome for the environment because it keeps the soil and water clean, which makes all sorts of plants and critters happy. But it's also a bit more work.  It takes extra effort to keep those pesky bugs and weeds away without chemicals, and sometimes you lose more crops. It's like trying to build a castle out of marshmallows - it looks great, but it might not be as strong as a regular brick one.  

Then there are all these other things farmers do to help wildlife, like planting special plants, letting animals graze in different spots, and keeping those nasty invasive plants in check. All that extra work adds up, so it's no wonder farmers sometimes need a little help to make ends meet and keep the wildlife happy.

So, I found this cool piece of land near a town called Potrero. It's got all sorts of stuff growing on it - chaparral, grass, and oak trees - and it's right next to a big forest.  Lots of animals live there, some even endangered ones like the Stephens' kangaroo rat and the mountain yellow-legged frog.

This land has a cool history. Native Americans lived there for ages, then ranchers came along and raised cattle and chopped down trees for firewood.  It's been around for a long time, and now someone could make it into an awesome organic farm.

I found a real farm doing this kind of stuff nearby and checked out what kind of help the government offers.  It's pretty inspiring to see people working hard to grow good food and protect nature at the same time.

Yo, lemme tell ya somethin' 'bout culture, see?  It's like, way more than just what ya see on the surface. It's like, a whole vibe, y'know? Ain't no two cultures exactly alike, and sayin' somethin' like "all Russians are stubborn" or "all Japanese are nice" is just plain wrong.  It's like, yeah, there might be some truths there, but everyone's different, right?  The real deal is to get a feel for what makes a culture tick, how it plays into the deal, and how their way of thinkin' might affect things. 

When you're dealin' with folks from a different place, you're gonna see it through your own lens, and that's natural. But tryin' to understand 'em means lookin' at their history, their beliefs, their whole deal. You gotta respect it, even if it's different from your own. Especially if you're the one with less to bargain with, ya know?  It's like, if you're walkin' into their turf, show 'em some respect, understand their rules, and things'll go smoother.

Now, culture ain't just 'bout countries.  Even within a country, companies have their own vibes. Some are all about workin' hard, others are chill.  You can tell by how folks dress, how they talk, who they trust to do what.  Some companies encourage helpin' out, others are all about stickin' to the rules. Just look at all the different ways American companies operate, even in the same city.  And some cultures, they might seem more uniform at first, but that just means you gotta dig deeper, y'know?

Values, that's the real key. They're like, the reason behind everything. If a culture values lookin' good or keepin' the peace, they ain't gonna embarrass themselves or their boss just to win a deal.  If they value a tough bargain, they ain't gonna give up easy.  So, before you sit down at the table, get a feel for those values. 

But here's the thing:  gettin' to know the other guy personally can make a big difference too.  It's like, understand their values, but also, who they are.  That's how you make a real connection and get a good deal.

Alright, lemme break this down for ya. So, these two brainiacs, St. Anselm and St. Thomas, both think God's the real deal. They're like, "Yo, God exists!" But they go about proving it in totally different ways. Anselm's all, "Look inside yourself, dude! God's already there, man! You just gotta know it!" He's sayin' that faith, like, knowing somethin' without proof, is the key. Kinda like trustin' your gut, ya know? 

Then there's Thomas, who's like, "Nah, man, we need evidence! We gotta use our smarts!"  He lays out five reasons why God's gotta be real, like pieces of a puzzle, ya dig?  He's all about logic and facts.

Now, both these guys make some good points, but neither one, like, totally knocks it outta the park. 

It's kinda like this: Anselm's sayin' faith is enough, but can you really trust somethin' you can't see or touch? And Thomas is like, "Show me the proof!" but where do you even start lookin' for proof of somethin' bigger than everything? It's a head-scratcher, man.

Yo, lemme tell ya 'bout this dude, Buddha. He was born way back, like, way back in the day, like the 5th or 6th century BCE. This cat was a prince, but he went all zen and ditched the fancy life. He got super enlightened and started preachin', and his teachings became this thing called Buddhism. There's a bunch of different kinds of Buddhism, but the oldest one is called Theravada.  It's been around for like, 2500 years, and things have changed a bit since Buddha was around. Like in Sri Lanka, they got this water-cutting thing they do every year. Monks and regular folks do it, and it's kinda religious, even though Buddha never said nothin' about it.  It's like that, man, all kinds of stuff has changed, from the small stuff to the big stuff, the core stuff. The Theravada Buddhist peeps, both the monks and the regular folks, have had to tweak their beliefs over time. It's like, stuff happens, ya know? 

Now, listen up, 'cause we gotta talk about some special words. We're gonna use "internal" and "external" a lot. An internal force is somethin' that comes from inside the Buddhist crew, doesn't matter if you're a monk or not. An external force is anything from folks outside Buddhism. A hostile force is somethin' that wants to mess with Buddhism, like, hurt it or somethin'. A benign force is just chillin', not tryin' to help or hurt, but it might end up doin' one or the other by accident. We'll be usin' these words a lot, so pay attention.

First things first, let's break down the basics of Theravada Buddhism. Buddhists find safety in the "triple gem"—Buddha, Dhamma, and Sangha.  Dhamma is like the teachings, all written down in a bunch of books called the Tripitaka. You got the Sutta Pitaka, which is all the Buddha's sayings, the Vinaya Pitaka, which is like the rule book for monks, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka, which is all the deep, philosophical stuff. They talk about things like Anatta (no soul), Dukkha (life is suffering), and Anicca (everything changes).  Gettin' all this stuff down is how you escape Sansara, which is like this endless cycle of bein' born and dying. Along with Sansara, you gotta get rid of lobha (desire), dosa (hatred), and moha (delusion). Only then can you become enlightened.  The Vinaya Pitaka has rules for everyone, but the monks have a lot more. Regular folks gotta follow the five precepts: don't kill, don't lie, don't steal, don't be a jerk in love, and don't get wasted.  

The big idea in Buddhism is the Four Noble Truths. First, life is suffering (Dukkha). Second,  attaching to stuff causes suffering. Third, you can get rid of suffering. Fourth, there's a path to end suffering, which is called the Eightfold Path.

Alright, lemme tell ya about these two countries, the U.S. and Mexico. They used to be at each other's throats, like, for a super long time, 57 years, from way back in 1836 to 1893. It was a real showdown, kinda like when Mack sends those goofy robot dudes after us. 

Back in 1846, things really kicked off with the Mexican-American War. The U.S. went and stomped all over Mexico, snagged Texas and the Southwest, and basically said, "This is ours now!" 

But it wasn't just one big fight, ya know? There were a bunch of smaller skirmishes and arguments along the way. They couldn't see eye-to-eye on stuff like religion, culture, and who owned what. It's kinda like when Camo and Katt argue over who gets to use the TV remote.

This whole neighbor rivalry thing happens a lot, ya know? Countries that live near each other often butt heads over stuff. It's like when you have a sibling, you're always fighting over something, right? 

The U.S. and Mexico were like that, except on a much bigger scale. This dude Pletcher said that Mexico and Cuba were the only countries that really gave the U.S. a hard time diplomatically, and I guess that makes sense because they're right next door. Other countries in Latin America? Not so much.

Religion was a big deal too. Americans back then weren't too keen on Catholicism, kinda like how Sa2b freaks out when he sees a spider. It all went back to the old days, when the English and Spanish were constantly at odds.  

Those 57 years had a ton of drama, like 17 different disputes!  Most of it was about border stuff, with bandits and outlaws causing trouble on both sides. It wasn't until both countries decided to crack down that things calmed down a bit.


Eventually, Mexico realized they needed the U.S. for stuff, and the U.S. shifted its focus from taking over land to, well, meddling in Mexico's economy. That's how the rivalry finally died down.

Fifteen years back, bam! I got hit with a nasty illness outta nowhere.  Didn't even know it existed!  See, I was a nurse, always thought that was the safest bet. "You'll always have a job, people gotta get sick, right?" That's what everyone kept sayin'. So, even though I dreamed of being a scientist or a journalist, maybe both, I stuck with nursing.  

But here I was, 46, single, with nothin' saved up and no way to work. Still disabled fifteen years later, livin' on Social Security, and lemme tell ya, I've got nothin' to call my own anymore.  Every day's a struggle, a fight just to feel safe and good about myself.   nothin's for sure anymore, except for one thing: I wouldn't have made it without my family and a few real good friends. Believe me, when disaster hits, you don't feel so tough.

Life throws curveballs, big and small, no matter how prepared you are.  Sometimes you need a hand. I get that we shouldn't rely on the government for everything, but wouldn't it be better if we learned to trust each other again? Help each other out, ask for help when we need it. Instead of building our own little bunkers, maybe we should be building each other up.

Those conservatives talk about "rugged individualism" building this country, but it was compassion, respect, and sharing that got our ancestors through tough times. Those pioneers crossing the Rockies didn't do it alone, they relied on each other. 


So, yeah, be prepared. I am. I got my emergency kit, first aid stuff, water tablets, and even plastic sheeting for a bio attack. Flashlights, batteries, candles, matches, canned goods, the whole shebang. If you got the space, grow your own food.  Get a wood stove, if you can.  

But while you're at it, get to know your neighbors. You never know when you might need 'em.

Alright, so how come critters end up looking the way they do?  Is there some kinda rulebook for evolution, ya know?  Back in the day, this guy D'Arcy Thompson, way back in 1917,  said something like, "Even today, scientists are just starting to figure out how to describe even the simplest creatures with math." And guess what? That's still kinda true!  But,  people are gettin' better at using math to figure out how shells grow,  like in those fancy clam things called mollusks.  We're trying to do the same thing with these cool snails called Prunum. We're using  math models and, like,  actual experiments to see how these snails change over time, and why they look the way they do.

Think of a shell like a tube that's always on the move, spiraling around and around. Each twist is called a whorl, and it's all wrapped around this imaginary line called the columella, kinda like the center of the spiral. The size of each whorl can change, and the lines between them are called sutures. Usually, the biggest whorl is the last one, the one that's kind of like the "belly" of the snail.  All the other whorls make up the spire,  and the very tip is called the apex.

You can look at a shell in different ways, like from the top, the bottom, the opening, or even the opposite side of the opening.  

To count the whorls, you gotta look at it from the top, find the first suture, and draw a line. Then, count all the whorls from that line, even if they're just a little bit there.

Basically, a shell is like a bunch of tiny doors opening up as the snail grows.  We can track these doors across space and time to see how the snail built its shell. We can even use math to figure out how the snail made its shell!  With enough math, we can change things up and see how the snail would look if it grew differently.

Alright, so listen up!  Indonesia's doin' alright, ya know? They're crushin' it with the water and sanitation stuff, gettin' close to those Millennium Development Goals. But when it comes to takin' care of moms and babies, they're fallin' behind.  Like, way behind. It's like, "Hey, we got clean water, but your kid's, like, dyin' from diarrhea."  Makes ya scratch your head, right?

See, they're sayin' more moms are havin' babies with those fancy "skilled workers" around. But here's the kicker: some of these "skilled workers" are just midwives, not doctors.  So, yeah, they're makin' progress, but not the kinda progress that saves lives.

And they're not doin' so hot with kids either.  Fewer and fewer kiddos are gettin' help when they're sick, and postnatal care?  Forget about it!  It's practically non-existant.

Now, here's the real doozy:  Cesarean sections are way down, like, only 4%. That's low, man, way too low. It's even worse in the country, only 2% compared to 7% in the city.  It's like they're forgettin' about the people who need it most. And the really messed up part? The poor folks, they're strugglin' to even get healthcare.  They're gettin' left behind.

So, what's the solution?  Should they build more programs or just fix the whole healthcare system? You gotta hand it to the programs, they're quick and easy.  But here's the downside: programs often suck the money and people away from other important stuff.  It's like, "Hey, we got this HIV program, everyone go there!"  While other stuff gets ignored.

Plus, when you got a bunch of different programs runnin' around, it gets messy.  You got paperwork everywhere, supplies gettin' lost, and nobody knows what's goin' on.

So, these Victorian books, they're all about fancy stuff and rich people, right?  But then you got these two books, "Oliver Twist" and "Wuthering Heights," they're like, "Nope, forget that!" They're all about mysteries and weird stuff, which wasn't really a thing back then.  It makes the characters way more interesting, 'cause you get to see what's really going on in their heads.

Like, take Oliver, he's got all these crazy dreams, like he's back with those mean guys, Sikes and Crackit, arguing and stuff. Then BAM!  Gunshots, chaos, lights flashing, he's being dragged away. It's all super confusing and scary, and you can tell Oliver's hurting, both physically and mentally.


Both of these books use dreams and crazy stuff to show us what's really going on inside the characters.  In "Oliver Twist," Oliver's dreams are like windows into his soul, showing us what's bothering him and how he's feeling about everything that's happening. When he gets shot, he has this flashback, like a dream, where he relives the whole thing.  He's trapped, he can't control anything, and all he feels is pain. It's like the world is against him, and he's just a helpless pawn.  It makes you wonder, who's really in charge of his life?  And it makes you feel sorry for him, 'cause he's just a kid trying to survive in a cruel world. 

 "Wuthering Heights" does the dream thing too, but it's a bit more...intense.  It's all about secrets and hidden feelings, and the dreams are like these creepy little glimpses into the characters' dark side.

A couple years back, I was workin' at this after-school program, you know, helpin' out those little elementary kids with their schoolwork. I was pretty good at English and readin', so that's mostly what I stuck to. One day, I got roped into helpin' this little dude named Adrian, I think he was in third or fourth grade, couldn't read worth a lick. Now, this kid, he speaks perfect English,  but somethin' just wasn't right. He'd nail some letters, then completely butcher others, super weird, ya know? I figured he was Latino, but maybe his English was new to him.  We struggled for ages, until one day, Adrian's mom showed up.  Now, she didn't speak a lick of English, just Spanish.  I was tryin' to piece together what she was sayin' with my super rusty Spanish (I was just learnin' back then).  Then it hit me like a ton of bricks: Adrian could read fine, he just wasn't familiar with the English alphabet!  I don't know if it made a difference in the long run, but I hope that fella's doin' alright.

See, that story's why I gotta talk about this whole language barrier thing in schools, especially here in California. It ain't always as obvious as it seems.
